So again Zeno, pleading for the Magnesians, begged with tears that they would not ascribe to the whole city tlte insanity of one man: that each one’s madness must be at his own risle. And the Rhodians, before the Senate, separate the public cause from that of private persons, saying that there is no city which has not often wicked citizens, and always a senseless mob. So the father is not bound by the delict of the son, nor the master by that of the servant, except there be some cause of blame in themselves,
